@NODE "Description" "Description"

   @{U}@{B}DESCRIPTION@{UU}@{UB}

   While there is no doubt that the Amiga is suffering from the lack of a
   lot of applications and resources which its fond users keep dreaming
   about, it is sure that you have got an abundant and varied choice of
   utilities designed to start your programs from Workbench. So, why yet
   another tool with the same purpose? To find out this, please read the
   following list which points out the main features of @{B}MiraWizRUN@{UB}:
   if you decide to try it, it means that you're not fully satisfied with the
   possibilities offered by the tool you are currently using, and that you
   always dreamt of a more pure and functional simplicity. Do you now
   understand why @{B}MiraWizRUN@{UB} was born?


   - @{B}MiraWizRUN@{UB} is a tool to start applications (and more) from
                your WB.

   - @{B}MiraWizRUN@{UB} does not require any configuration change when you
                add or remove programs from your hard disk!

   - @{B}MiraWizRUN@{UB} opens a window on your WB, offering a clear and
                immediate access to all of its functions. The programs are
                sorted by category, using the same order you adopted on your
                hard disk, so you will immediately feel at ease when
                browsing through MiraWizRUN's lists just like you do with
                drawers and windows on your Workbench.

   - @{B}MiraWizRUN@{UB} is a browser which creates a complete list of the
                executable files contained in the DOS paths you will choose.

   - @{B}MiraWizRUN@{UB} starts the program in WB mode, as if you
                double-clicked on its icon: this way the program will be
                launched according to the settings defined in its ".info"
                file: stack size, tooltypes, etc...

   - @{B}MiraWizRUN@{UB} also allows you to freely define an alternative
                action, besides starting the program. As an example, if you
                use Scalos you could associate the action to the OpenDrawer
                command, so being able to choose between starting a program
                or opening the drawer which contains it, without the need to
                go through all the windows in the path. Or you could use one
                of the many available tools to edit ".info" files: this way
                you will be able to directly open the icon info window for
                the program to change a tooltype, and then immediately
                launch the program itself, all this without the need to open
                a single WB window.

   - @{B}MiraWizRUN@{UB} bases its operation upon some external commands
                which you will be able to define in the @{" preferences " LINK "Preferences"}
                window.

   - @{B}MiraWizRUN@{UB} relies on MUI for a perfect integration with your
                WB. Please don't forget that its window will always have to
                be visible, so you will need maximum configurability...

   - @{B}MiraWizRUN@{UB} does not create external preferences files, and its
                executable file is just 20Kb long.


   ...but actually describing all the qualities of @{B}MiraWizRUN@{UB} is
   not an easy task :), it's better to try it "on the field" to realize how
   much can it do, and then immediately proceed to its @{" installation " LINK "Installation"}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Compatibility" "Compatibility"

   @{U}@{B}COMPATIBILITY@{UU}@{UB}

   For a correct usage of MiraWizRUN v1.0 you need:

   @{U}REQUIRED@{UU}:

   - @{B}MUI version 3.0 or higher.@{UB}
     @{I}author@{UI} Stefan Stuntz
     @{I}aminet/util/libs/mui3xusr.lha@{UI}

   - @{B}The "Nlist" MUI extension@{UB}
     @{I}author@{UI} Gilles Masson
     @{I}aminet/dev/mui/MCC_NListxxx.lha@{UI}

   - @{B}The original "List" AmigaDOS command@{UB}


   @{U}RECOMMENDED@{UU}:

   - @{B}The "WBRun" command@{UB}
     @{I}authors@{UI} Sylvain Rougier & Pierre Carrette
     @{I}aminet/util/cli/WBRun_fix.lha@{UI}

   - @{B}Parm.library@{UB}
     @{I}authors@{UI} Sylvain Rougier & Pierre Carrette
     @{I}included in the WBRun archive@{UI}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Installation" "Installation"

   @{U}@{B}INSTALLATION@{UU}@{UB}

   By default, the program relies on the fact that you are going to use
   @{B}WBRun@{UB} as the external command to start applications.
   So you should first of all install this command in the "@{B}C:@{UB}"
   drawer on your system, while you'll have to copy to "@{B}LIBS:@{UB}" the
   "@{B}Parm.library@{UB}" file which is distributed in the same archive as
   WBRun.
   @{i}(Read in the@{ui} @{" compatibility " LINK "Compatibility"} @{i}section where to find it)@{ui}


   When you've done this, installing @{B}MiraWizRUN@{UB} simply requires
   copying its executable file and the corresponding icon wherever you
   prefer. If the chosen destination is the @{B}WBStartup@{UB} drawer, then
   please remember that you'll have to add the @{B}DONOTWAIT@{UB} tooltype
   in @{B}MiraWizRUN@{UB} icon.

   Before starting @{B}MiraWizRUN@{UB}, anyway, you will have to edit its
   default tooltypes to adapt them to your preferences and to the correct
   paths in your system. You will see the tooltypes listed with progressive
   names (@{B}PATH_xx=@{UB}), followed by a @{b}title@{ub}, a separating
   "@{B}|@{UB}" character and the @{b}DOS path@{ub} which @{B}MiraWizRUN@{UB} will show.

   You may increase or reduce the number of @{b}PATH@{ub} entries as you like,
   and edit in the same way the corresponding titles and paths, so that they
   fit your system.


   That's good: @{B}MiraWizRUN@{UB} is now ready to be @{" used " LINK "Usage"}! :)

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Usage" "Usage"

   @{U}@{B}USAGE@{UU}@{UB}

   @{B}1)@{UB} Click on any item in the upper list to show the names of
      available files in the selected category.

   @{B}2)@{UB} Click on the name of the file to start, or on the gadget on
      its right to execute the alternative action.

      @{B}And this is all! :)@{UB}



   Please note that through the menus or the "@{B}AMIGA+I@{UB}" keyboard
   shortcut you can invert the filter effect while using
   @{B}MiraWizRUN@{UB}: so any name matching the set pattern will alternate
   between being shown and hidden, and the list will be updated. Here is the
   use for this: if, for example, "@{I}guide@{UI}" and "@{I}doc@{UI}" files
   are normally hidden by the filter, they can be shown by selecting "@{b}Invert@{ub}
   @{b}filter@{ub}". This makes it possible to directly reach and open the
   documentation of the program you are going to run, without the need to
   open any WB window to achieve this.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Preferences" "Preferences"

   @{U}@{B}PREFERENCES@{UU}@{UB}

   The upper part of the preferences window contains a default @{I}@{B}pattern@{UI}@{UB}
   which you can edit to @{b}filter@{ub} out any files you don't want to be
   shown amongst the accessible ones.

   The best thing you can do to understand the function of the central part
   of the window @{I}(@{B}Show Hide@{UB})@{UI} is trying to activate the 4
   switches contained therein: the main program window will immediately be
   updated accordingly, adapting to the requested look.

   The @{I}@{B}Action@{UI}@{UB} part is used to make @{B}MiraWizRUN@{UB} know
   which external DOS commands have to be used to execute its functions. The
   cycle gadget tells if the secondary alternative action will have to
   affect the file directly or the drawer containing it. The string gadget
   on the right contains the command name. Below, a second cycle gadget
   lets you choose whether MiraWizRUN will have to execute the
   actions on a single or a double click of the left mouse button. On the
   right you have to insert the name of a DOS command which can execute
   files in Workbench mode (such as @{B}WBRun@{UB}, for example: please
   read its documentation for more info about the requirements...).

   Finally, the window contains a @{I}@{B}Test file@{UI}@{UB} switch: it is
   another filter to hide icons which are not associated to an executable
   file with the same name, such as, for example, @{I}Sys:System/Shell.info@{UI}.


   After performing any change you like in this window, you will not need to
   save the new settings: they will be stored and used simply when quitting
   by clicking on the close gadget.

   Configuring the look of the window, fonts and any other cosmetic detail
   will of course have to be done using the MUI preferences module.

@ENDNODE
